\part{PianoScript Music Notation}
\section*{Basics}
PianoScript in short is a pianoroll in a readable design as music notation. The notation includes of course a lot of elements. We start with the basics:
\begin{itemize}
\item{\subsubsection*{Notes} 
Pitch is expressed on a twelve tone staff. As you can see on the first page of this document, the staff exists from groups of two and three line that are connected to a miniature pianokeyboard(only on the first line of a music document) and thus, are the black keys.

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=1]{cminor.jpg}
\end{center}
\[
\emph{\small picture 1: a c minor chord on the PianoScript staff} 
\]

The notes are black or white depending on the color of the pianokey. This means that all black notes are on top of a staff-line while all white notes are in between or against a staff-line.
}

\newpage

\item{
\subsubsection*{Rhythm}

Rhythm is expressed in distance like in a pianoroll editor or inside 'Synthesia' youtube videos.

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=1]{moonlightfirstbar.jpg}
\end{center}
\[
\emph{\small picture 2: the first bar of the moonlight sonata} 
\]

This example bar is written in 4/4 time-signature. We divide the length of the bar in four equal pieces and thus every 'grid space' is one \underline{quarter} note long. 

If we follow the logic of relatively reading the rhythm: There are two notes with a duration of a \underline{whole} note(four quarters/grid spaces). The grouped notes on the right side are all a equal length. There fit three notes in a quarter grid space so these are \underline{quarter triplets}.

}
